stcode area|BL1-BL7]], [[M postcode area|M26]]\n|area_code = 01204, 01942, 0161\n|twin1 = [[Le Mans]]\n|twin1_country = {{Flagicon|France}} France\n|twin2 = [[Paderborn]]\n|twin2_country = {{Flagicon|Germany}}  (Germany)\n|blank_name = [[ISO 3166-2:GB|ISO 3166-2]]\n|blank_info = GB-BOL\n|blank1_name = [[ONS coding system|ONS code]]\n|blank1_info = 00BL (ONS)<br />E08000001 (GSS)\n|blank2_name = [[British national grid reference system|OS grid reference]]\n|blank2_info = {{gbmappingsmall|SD715095}}\n|blank3_name = [[Nomenclature of Territorial Units for Statistics|NUTS]] 3\n|blank3_info = UKD32\n|footnotes =\n|website = http://www.bolton.gov.uk\n}}\nThe '''Metropolitan Borough of Bolton''' {{IPAc-en|audio=en-uk-Bolton.ogg|\u02c8|b|o\u028a|l|t|\u0259n}} is a [[metropolitan borough]] of [[Greater Manchester]], England, named after its largest town, [[Bolton]], but covering a far larger area which includes [[Blackrod]], [[Farnworth]], [[Horwich]], [[Kearsley]], \n[[Westhoughton]], and part of the [[West Pennine Moors]]. It has a population of 276,800.\n\nThe boundaries were set by of the [[Local Government Act 1972]], and cover eight former local government districts; seven [[Urban district (Great Britain and Ireland)|Urban District]]s from the [[administrative counties of England|administrative county]] of [[Lancashire]], and the [[County Borough of Bolton]]. The metropolitan districts of [[Metropolitan Borough of Bury|Bury]], [[City of Salford|Salford]] and [[Metropolitan Borough of Wigan|Wigan]] lie to the east, south and west respectively; and the non-metropolitan districts of [[Blackburn with Darwen]] and [[Borough of Chorley|Chorley]] in Lancashire to the north and north-west.\n\n==History==\nThe metropolitan borough was formed on 1 April 1974, by the merger of the [[County Borough of Bolton]] and the following districts from the [[Administrative counties of England|administrative county]] of [[Lancashire]]:\n\n*[[Municipal Borough of Farnworth]]\n*[[Blackrod Urban District|Urban District of Blackrod]]\n*[[Horwich Urban District|Urban District of Horwich]]\n*[[Kearsley Urban District|Urban District of Kearsley]]\n*[[Little Lever Urban District|Urban District of Little Lever]]\n*[[Westhoughton Urban District|Urban District of Westhoughton]]\n*the southern part of [[Turton Urban District]], specifically the villages of [[Bradshaw, Greater Manchester|Bradshaw]], [[Bromley Cross]], [[Dunscar]], [[Egerton, Greater Manchester|Egerton]] and [[Harwood, Greater Manchester|Harwood]]. This area is now known as [[South Turton]].\n\nBolton Council unsuccessfully petitioned [[Elizabeth II]] for the Metropolitan Borough of Bolton to be granted [[city status in the United Kingdom|city status]] in 1992 (the Queen's 40th year as monarch), in 2000 (for the Millennium celebrations), in 2002 (Queen's Golden Jubilee), and 2012 (Queen's Diamond Jubilee).<ref name=city>{{cite web|url=http://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/comment/boltoncolumnists/8794606.It___s_still_worth_trying_again_for_city_status/|title=It's still worth trying again for city status|accessdate=20 January 2011|date=17 January 2011|publisher=theboltonnews.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Parishes==\nHorwich, Westhoughton and Blackrod are now constituted as [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]]es. There are three [[town council]]s in the metropolitan borough, Westhoughton Town Council, [[Horwich Town Council]] and Blackrod Town Council. The rest of the metropolitan borough, Bolton, Farnworth, Kearsley, Little Lever, and South Turton, have remained [[unparished area]]s since 1974.\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to the 2009 estimates,<ref>{{Citation|title=2009 Mid Year Estimates \u2013 Table 9 ONS|url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/statbase/Product.asp?vlnk=15106| accessdate=9 September 2010}}</ref> of the 265,100 people living in Bolton Metropolitan Borough, the following ethnicities have been recorded:\n\n*88.0% '''White'''\n**85.9% [[White British]]\n**1.2% [[Other White]]\n**0.8% [[Irish Briton|White Irish]]\n*9.3% '''South Asian'''\n**5.9% [[British Asian|Indian]]\n**2.7% [[British Asian|Pakistani]]\n**0.5% [[British Asian|Other South Asian]]\n**0.2% [[British Asian|Bangladeshi]]\n*1.2% '''Mixed Race'''\n**0.5% [[British Mixed|White and Asian]]\n**0.4% [[British Mixed|White and Black Caribbean]]\n**0.2% [[British Mixed|White and Black African]]\n**0.2% [[British Mixed|Other Mixed]]\n*1.0% '''Black'''\n**0.6% [[Black British|Black African]]\n**0.4% [[Black British|Black Caribbean]]\n**0.1% [[Black British|Other Black]]\n*0.6% '''Other'''\n**0.3% [[British Chinese|Chinese]]\n**0.3% [[Other ethnic group (United Kingdom Census)|Other]]\n\n===Population change===\nThe table below details the population change since 1801, including the percentage change since the last available census data. Although the Metropolitan Borough of Bolton has only existed since 1974, figures have been generated by combining data from the towns, villages, and [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]]es that would later be constituent parts of the borough.\n\n{{historical populations\n| title = [[Population growth]] in Bolton since 1801\n| align = centre\n| shading = off\n| pop_name = Population\n| percentages = on\n| cols = 3\n| 1801 | 37417\n| 1811 | 48996\n| 1821 | 60319\n| 1831 | 75787\n| 1841 | 89507\n| 1851 | 105957\n| 1861 | 132437\n| 1871 | 158917\n| 1881 | 185397\n| 1891 | 216792\n| 1901 | 240014\n| 1911 | 265733\n| 1921 | 263413\n| 1931 | 261119\n| 1941 | 256207\n| 1951 | 251388\n| 1961 | 255627\n| 1971 | 259993\n| 1981 | 260229\n| 1991 | 262880\n| 2001 | 261035\n| align-fn=center\n| footnote = Pre-1974 statistics were gathered from local government areas that now comprise the Metropolitan Borough of Bolton<br />''Source: Vision of Britain''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/unit/10057061/cube/TOT_POP#tab02 |title=Bolton District: total population |publisher=Vision of Britain}} Retrieved on 20 December 2008.</ref>\n}}\n\n==Transport==\nThe Bolton metropolitan area is served by the following railway stations:\n\n*[[Bolton railway station|Bolton Trinity Street]] \u2013 a town-centre transport interchange\n*[[Bromley Cross railway station|Bromley Cross]]\n*[[Hall i' th' Wood railway station|Hall i' th' Wood]]\n*[[Blackrod railway station|Blackrod]]\n*[[Horwich Parkway railway station|Horwich Parkway]] (for the [[University of Bolton Stadium]] \u2013 [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]])\n*[[Lostock railway station|Lostock]]\n*[[Westhoughton railway station|Westhoughton]]\n*[[Moses Gate railway station|Moses Gate]]\n*[[Farnworth railway station|Farnworth]]\n*[[Kearsley railway station|Kearsley]]\n*[[Daisy Hill railway station|Daisy Hill]]\n\n==Education==\n{{See also|List of schools in Bolton}}\nIn 2007, Bolton was ranked 69th out of the 149 [[Local Education Authority|Local Education Authorities]] \u2013 and sixth out of ten in Greater Manchester \u2013 for its [[National Curriculum assessment]] performance.<ref name=\"LEA2007\">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/7130024.stm |title=LEA SATs performance |publisher=BBC |date=6 December 2007 |accessdate=25 March 2008 | location=London}}</ref> Measured on the percentage of pupils attaining at least 5 A*\u2013C grades at [[GCSE]] including maths and English, the Bolton LEA was 111th out of 149: 40.1% of pupils achieved this objective, against a national average of 46.7%.<ref name=\"5A-C2007\">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/7180228.stm |title=How different LEAs performed |publisher=BBC |date=10 January 2008 |accessdate=23 January 2008 | location=London}}</ref> Unauthorised absence from Bolton's secondary schools in the 2006/2007 academic year was 1.4%, in line with the national average, and authorised absence was 6.0% against the national average of 6.4%.<ref name=\"Absence\">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/education/07/school_tables/secondary_schools/html/350_6017.stm |title=Secondary schools in Bolton |publisher=BBC |date=10 January 2008 |accessdate=25 March 2008 | location=London}}</ref> At GCSE level, [[Bolton School]] (Girls' Division) was the most successful of Bolton's 21 secondary schools, with 99% of pupils achieving at least 5 A*\u2013C grades at including maths and English.<ref name=\"gcsesuccess\">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/education/07/school_tables/secondary_schools/html/350_gcse_lea.stm |title=Secondary schools in Bolton: GCSE-level |publisher=BBC |date=10 January 2008 |accessdate=25 March 2008 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nThe [[University of Bolton]] is one of Greater Manchester's four universities. In 2008, [[The Times]] Good University Guide ranked it 111th of 113 institutions in Britain.<ref name=\"TimesGUG\">{{cite web|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/education/good_university_guide/article2102878.ece|title=The University of Bolton|accessdate=25 March 2008|work=Times Online: Good University Guide website |publisher=Times Online (Times Newspapers Ltd)|date=15 August 2007| location=London}}</ref> There are 4,440 students (83% undergraduate, 17% postgraduate); 2.6% come from outside Britain.  In 2007 there were 8.8 applications for every place, and student satisfaction was recorded as 74.4%. It is one of Britain's newest universities, having been given this status in 2005.<ref name=\"STimesUG\">{{cite web|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/education/sunday_times_university_guide/article2490058.ece|title=University of Bolton|accessdate=25 March 2008|work=The Sunday Times University Guide website |publisher=The Sunday Times (Times Newspapers Ltd)|date=23 September 2007| location=London}}</ref>\n\n===GCSE Examination Performance 2009===\n{{Metropolitan Borough of Bolton GCSE performances}}\n\n* ''The table on the left shows the percentage of students gaining five A* to C grades, including English and Maths, for secondary schools in the Metropolitan Borough of Bolton''.\n* ''The table on the right shows the Average Total Point Score per Student for secondary schools in the Metropolitan Borough of Bolton''.\n* ''Schools highlighted in yellow are above the LEA average; those highlighted in orange are below the average.''\n* ''Another secondary school, Bolton Muslim Girls' School, has opened since January 2007; no results are available.''\n* Source: Department for Children, Schools and Families{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n==Leaders of Bolton Council==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"95%\"\n! colspan=\"6\"|Leaders of Bolton Metropolitan Borough Council\n|-\n! No.\n! Leader\n! colspan=\"2\"|Political party\n! Period of office\n! Notes\n|-\n| align=center | 1 \n| [[John Hanscomb]]\n| style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| align=center | 1973\u20131980\n| <small>Chairman and Transitional Mayor of Bolton (1973\u20131974) <br />and ceremonial [[List of Mayors of Bolton|Mayor of Bolton]] (1982\u20131983)</small>\n|-\n| align=center | 2\n| [[Robert Howarth]]\n| style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| align=center | 1980\u20132004\n| <small>[[Member of Parliament|MP]] for [[Bolton East (UK Parliament constituency)|Bolton East]] (1964\u20131970)</small>\n|-\n| align=center | 3\n| [[Barbara Ronson]]\n| style=\"background-color: {{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]\n| align=center | 2004\u20132006\n| <small>[[Horwich Town Council#Mayors of Horwich|Mayor of Horwich]] (1996\u20131997) and Mayor of Bolton (2007\u20132008)</small>\n|-\n| align=center | 4\n| [[Clifford Morris]]\n| style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| Labour\n| align=center | 2006\u20132018\n| <small>Mayor of Bolton (2003\u20132004)</small>\n|-\n| align=center | 5\n| [[Linda Thomas (politician)|Linda Thomas]]\n| style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| Labour\n| align=center | 2018\u20132019\n| \n|-\n| align=center | 6\n| [[David Greenhalgh]]\n| style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| Conservative \n| align=center | 2019\u2013present\n| \n|}\n\n==Twin towns==\nThe Metropolitan Borough of Bolton has two twin towns, one in France and another in Germany.<ref>[http://www.bolton.gov.uk/website/Pages/Towntwinning.aspx Bolton Council : ''Town Twinning'']. Retrieved 8 January 2010</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \"text-align:left;font-size:100%;\"|\n|-\n! style=\"background: #811541; color: #FFFFFF\" !  |\n! style=\"background: #811541; color: #FFFFFF\" height=\"17\" width=\"120\" | Country\n! style=\"background: #810001; color: #FFFFFF\" !  |\n! style=\"background: #810001; color: #FFFFFF\" !  width=\"100\" | Place\n! style=\"background: #811541; color: #FFFFFF\" !  |\n! style=\"background: #811541; color: #FFFFFF\" !  width=\"130\" | County / District / Region / State\n! style=\"background: #811541; color: #FFFFFF\" !  width=\"130\" | Originally twinned with\n! style=\"background: #811541; color: #FFFFFF\" !  width=\"40\" | Date\n|-\n ! style=\"background: #FFFFEF; color: #000000\" !  | {{Flagicon|France}}\n|! style=\"background: #FFFFEF; color: #000000\" !  | France\n ! style=\"background: #FFFFCF; color: #000000\" !  | [[File:Blason de la ville de Le Mans (Sarthe).svg|25px]]\n|! style=\"background: #FFFFCF; color: #000000\" !  | '''[[Le Mans]]'''\n ! style=\"background: #FFFFEF; color: #000000\" !  | [[File:Pays-de-la-Loire flag.svg|25px]]\n|! style=\"background: #FFFFEF; color: #000000\" !  | ''[[Pays de la Loire]]''\n|! style=\"background: #FFFFEF; color: #000000\" !  | [[County Borough of Bolton]]\n|! style=\"background: #FFFFEF; color: #000000\" !  | 1973\n|-\n ! style=\"background: #FFFFEF; color: #000000\" !  | {{Flagicon|Germany}}\n|! style=\"background: #FFFFEF; color: #000000\" !  | Germany\n ! style=\"background: #FFFFCF; color: #000000\" !  | [[File:DEU Paderborn COA.svg|25px]]\n|! style=\"background: #FFFFCF; color: #000000\" !  | '''[[Paderborn]]'''\n ! style=\"background: #FFFFEF; color: #000000\" !  | [[File:Flag of North Rhine-Westphalia.svg|25px]]\n|! style=\"background: #FFFFEF; color: #000000\" !  | ''[[North Rhine-Westphalia|Nordrhein-Westfalen]]''\n|! style=\"background: #FFFFEF; color: #000000\" !  | Metropolitan Borough of Bolton\n|! style=\"background: #FFFFEF; color: #000000\" !  | 1975\n|-\n|}\n\n==Neighbouring districts==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" width=95%\n\n!colspan=6| The local government districts which surround the Metropolitan Borough of Bolton\n|-\n|align=center rowspan=2 width=25% |<small>'''North-West:'''</small><br/>[[Chorley (borough)|Borough of Chorley]]\n|align=center colspan=2 width=35%|<small>'''North:'''</small><br/>[[Blackburn with Darwen|Borough of Blackburn with Darwen]]\n|align=center rowspan=2 width=25%|<small>'''North-East''' and '''East''':</small><br/>[[Metropolitan Borough of Bury]]\n|-\n|align=center colspan=2 width=35%|<br /><span style=\"font-size:120%\">'''Metropolitan Borough of Bolton'''</span><br /><br />\n|-\n|align=center colspan=2 width=30%|<small>'''South-West:'''</small><br/>[[Metropolitan Borough of Wigan]]\n|align=center colspan=2 width=30%|<small>'''South-East:'''</small><br/>[[City of Salford]]\n|}\n\n==Freedom of the Borough==\nThe following people and military units have received the [[Freedom of the City|Freedom of the Borough]] of Merton.\n \n{{Expand list|date=July 2019}}\n\n===Individuals===\n* [[William Lever, 1st Viscount Leverhulme]]: 10 November 1902.\n* [[John Pennington Thomasson]]: 10 November 1902.\n* [[Andrew Carnegie]]: 29 September 1910.\n* [[Bernard Montgomery|FM Rt Hon Lord Montgomery]] {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100|sep= |KG|GCB|DSO|PC|DL}}: 5 November 1949.\n* [[Nat Lofthouse]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE}}: 2 December 1989.\n* [[Robert Howarth]]: 16 June 2001.\n\n===Military units===\n* 253rd Regiment [[Royal Artillery]] ([[Army Reserve (United Kingdom)|TA]]): 18 April 1964.\n* 5th Battalion [[Loyal Regiment (North Lancashire)]] ([[Army Reserve (United Kingdom)|TA]]): 18 April 1964.\n* [[HMS Dido (F104)|HMS Dido]], [[Royal Navy|RN]]: 14 April 1973.\n* 216 (The Bolton Artillery) Battery [[103rd (Lancashire Artillery Volunteers) Regiment Royal Artillery]]: 18 May 1994.\n* 1st Battalion The [[Duke of Lancaster's Regiment]]: 14 March 2009.\n\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boltonsmayors.org.uk/0-freedom.html|title=The Freedom of Bolton|website=www.boltonsmayors.org.uk}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bolton local elections]]\n*[[List of Mayors of Bolton]]\n*[[List of people from Bolton]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Metropolitan Borough of Bolton|Bolton}}\n{{wikivoyage|Bolton}}\n\n\n{{Greater Manchester}}\n{{NW_England}}\n{{Metropolitan districts of England}}\n{{Portal bar|Greater Manchester}}\n{{Coord|53|34|39|N|2|25|48|W|type:city_region:GB_source:nlwiki|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bolton, Metropolitan Borough of}}\n[[Category:Metropolitan Borough of Bolton| ]]\n[[Category:Local government in the Metropolitan Borough of Bolton|Bolton Metropolitan Borough]]\n[[Category:Metropolitan boroughs of Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:1974 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "Curly.fries12345", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metropolitan_Borough_of_Bolton"}
{"title_page": "Mark Jefferson (geographer)", "text_new": "'''Mark Jefferson''' (1863-1949) was the chief cartographer of the American Delegation to the [[Paris Peace Conference, 1919|Paris Peace Conference]] in 1919.  He was also the head of the geography department at Michigan State Normal College (MSNC), now [[Eastern Michigan University]] (EMU), from 1901-1939.\n\nJefferson received his bachelor's degree from [[Boston University]] and his master's degree from [[Harvard University]].  From 1883-1889 he worked at an astronomical observatory in Argentina.  From 1890-1901 he was a high school teacher in Massachusetts.  In addition to teaching at MSNC he also taught at the Harvard Summer School.  Among Jefferson's students were geographers \n[[Isaiah Bowman]] and [[Charles C. Colby]].\n\nIn 1916 Jefferson served as president of the [[American Association of Geographers]].\n\nA biography of Jefferson entitled ''Mark Jefferson: Geographer'' written by [[Geoffrey J. Martin]] was published by Eastern Michigan University Press in 1968.  EMU has a building named after Mark Jefferson.\n\n==Sources==\n*[https://www.webcitation.org/67vPKD5ON?url=http://www.csiss.org/classics/content/12 CSISS article based on Jefferson's work]\n*''Aurora'' (MSNC yearbook) 1918.\n*[https://www.jstor.org/stable/2561235 ''Annals of the American Association of Geographers'' Vol. 39, no. 4]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jefferson, Mark}}\n[[Category:1863 births]]\n[[Category:Boston University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Eastern Michigan University faculty]]\n[[Category:Harvard Summer School instructors]]\n[[Category:American geographers]]\n[[Category:1949 deaths]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the American Association of Geographers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Mark Jefferson''' (1863-1949) was the chief cartographer of the American Delegation to the [[Paris Peace Conference, 1919|Paris Peace Conference]] in 1919.  He was also the head of the geography department at Michigan State Normal College (MSNC), now [[Eastern Michigan University]] (EMU), from 1901-1939.\n\nJefferson received his bachelor's degree from [[Boston University]] and his master's degree from [[Harvard University]].  From 1883-1889 he worked at an astronomical observatory in Argentina.  From 1890-1901 he was a high school teacher in Massachusetts.  In addition to teaching at MSNC he also taught at the Harvard Summer School.  Among Jefferson's students were geographers \n[[Isaiah Bowman]] and [[Charles C. Colby]].\n\nIn 1916 Jefferson served as president of the [[American Association of Geographers]].\n\nA biography of Jefferson entitled ''Mark Jefferson geographer'' written by [[Geoffrey J. Martin]] was published by Eastern Michigan University Press in 1968.  EMU has a building named after Mark Jefferson.\n\n==Sources==\n*[https://www.webcitation.org/67vPKD5ON?url=http://www.csiss.org/classics/content/12 CSISS article based on Jefferson's work]\n*''Aurora'' (MSNC yearbook) 1918.\n*[https://www.jstor.org/stable/2561235 ''Annals of the American Association of Geographers'' Vol. 39, no. 4]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jefferson, Mark}}\n[[Category:1863 births]]\n[[Category:Boston University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Eastern Michigan University faculty]]\n[[Category:Harvard Summer School instructors]]\n[[Category:American geographers]]\n[[Category:1949 deaths]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the American Association of Geographers]]\n", "name_user": "TheAwesomeAtom", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed book title", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Jefferson_(geographer)"}
{"title_page": "Mars Helicopter Ingenuity", "text_new": "<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout, and guidelines. -->\n{{short description|A planned robotic Mars aircraft}}\n{{about|the planned NASA robotic helicopter being deployed on Mars in 2021|Mars helicopters in general|Mars aircraft}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name                  = Ingenuity\n| names_list            = Mars Helicopter Scout<ref name=\"MHS\">\"[https://pub-lib.jpl.nasa.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-3749/03_Rotorcrafts%20For%20Mars%20Exploration_Balaram.pdf Rotorcrafts for Mars Exploration: Mars Helicopter Scout]\" \u2013 [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]], 19 June 2014</ref><ref name='distance'/>\n\n<!--image of the spacecraft/mission-->\n| image                 = File:PIA22460-Mars2020Mission-Helicopter-20180525 (cropped).jpg\n| image_caption         = Artist concept of the Mars Helicopter on the surface of Mars\n\n<!--Basic details-->\n| mission_type          = Technology demonstrator\n| operator              = [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]]\n| website               = {{url|https://mars.nasa.gov/technology/helicopter/}}\n| mission_duration      = 30 days (planned)<ref name=\"spacenews 20180504\" />\n| distance_travelled    = \n\n<!--Spacecraft properties-->\n| spacecraft            = <!--Spacecraft name/serial number (eg. Space Shuttle ''Discovery'', Apollo CM-118), etc-->\n| spacecraft_type       = [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|UAV]] [[helicopter]]\n| spacecraft_bus        = <!--eg. A2100M, Star-2, etc-->\n| manufacturer          = Jet Propulsion Laboratory\n| launch_mass           = <!--fuelled mass at launch, not including rocket or upper stage-->\n| BOL_mass              = <!--spacecraft mass in orbit at beginning of operational life, after LEOP phase-->\n| landing_mass          = {{cvt|1.8|kg}}<ref name='distance'/><!--Mass after landing (recovered spacecraft only)-->\n| dry_mass              = <!--spacecraft mass in orbit without fuel-->\n| payload_mass          = <!--Mass of cargo carried by spacecraft (eg. for Space Shuttle), or total mass of instrumentation/equipment/experiments for mission-->\n| dimensions            = Chassis: {{cvt|14|cm}} cube<ref name='Aung May2018'/><br/>Rotor diameter: {{cvt|1.2|m}}<ref name='Aung May2018'/><br/>Height: {{cvt|0.8|m}}<ref name='Aung May2018'/>\n| power                 = {{cvt|220|W}}<ref name='distance'/>\n\n<!--Launch details-->\n| launch_date           = 17 July to 5 August 2020<ref name=\"NASAoverview\">{{Cite web|url=http://mars.nasa.gov/mars2020/mission/overview/|title=Overview - Mars 2020 Rover|last=mars.nasa.gov|website=mars.nasa.gov|access-date=19 February 2019}}</ref>\n| launch_rocket         = [[Atlas V|Atlas V 541]]<ref name=\"Launchvehicle\">{{cite news|url=http://spaceflightnow.com/2016/07/25/nasa-books-nuclear-certified-atlas-5-rocket-for-mars-2020-rover-launch/ |title=NASA books nuclear-certified Atlas 5 rocket for Mars 2020 rover launch|work=Spaceflight Now|first=Justin|last=Ray|date=25 July 2016|accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n| launch_site           = [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]], [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station Space Launch Complex 41|SLC-41]]\n| launch_contractor     = [[United Launch Alliance]]\n| deployment_from       = [[Mars 2020|''Perseverance'' rover]]\n| deployment_date       = <!--date deployed-->\n| entered_service       = <!--date on which the spacecraft entered service, if it did not do so immediately after launch-->\n\n<!--end of mission-->\n| disposal_type         = <!--Whether the spacecraft was deorbited, decommissioned, placed in a graveyard orbit, etc-->\n| declared              = <!--when the operator/agency officially ended the mission-->\n| deactivated           = <!--when craft was decommissioned-->\n| destroyed             = <!--when craft was destroyed (if other than by re-entry)-->\n| last_contact          = <!--when last signal received if not decommissioned-->\n| recovery_by           = <!--recovered by-->\n| recovery_date         = <!--recovery date-->\n| decay_date            = <!--when craft re-entered the atmosphere, not needed if it landed-->\n| landing_date          = <!--when the spacecraft made a controlled landing, not needed if it did not return intact-->\n| landing_site          = <!--where the craft landed; site/runway or coordinates-->\n<!--\n    The following template should be used for ONE of the three above fields \"end_of_mission\", \"decay\" or \"landing\" if the spacecraft is no longer operational.\n    If it landed intact, use it for the landing time, otherwise for the date it ceased operations, or the decay date if it was still operational when it re-entered.\n    {{end-date|DATE, TIME}} UTC (for Zulu/UTC) or {{end-date|DATE}} (if time unknown)\n-->\n\n|interplanetary         = <!--Infobox spaceflight/IP can be called multiple times for missions with multiple targets or combined orbiter/lander missions, etc-->\n {{Infobox spaceflight/IP\n   |type                = aircraft\n   |object              = [[Mars]]\n   |component           = Helicopter\n   |arrival_date        = 18 February 2021<ref name=\"NASAoverview\"/>\n   |location            = [[Jezero crater]]\n   |distance            = Up to {{cvt|300|m}} per flight (planned)<ref name='Balaram 2018'/>\n }}\n\n<!--transponder parameters-->\n| trans_band            = <!--Transponder frequency bands-->\n| trans_frequency       = <!--specific frequencies-->\n| trans_bandwidth       = <!--bandwidth-->\n| trans_capacity        = <!--capacity of the transponders-->\n| trans_coverage        = <!--area covered-->\n| trans_TWTA            = <!--TWTA output power-->\n| trans_EIRP            = <!--equivalent isotropic power-->\n| trans_HPBW            = <!--half-power beam width-->\n\n<!--Only use where a spacecraft/mission is part of a clear programme of sequential missions.\nIf in doubt, leave it out-->\n| programme             = \n| previous_mission      = \n| next_mission          = \n| programme2            = \n| previous_mission2     = \n| next_mission2         = \n\n<!--mission insignia or patch-->\n| insignia              = File:Mars Helicopter JPL insignia.svg\n| insignia_caption      = JPL's Mars Helicopter insignia\n| insignia_alt          = <!--image alt text-->\n| insignia_size         = <!--include px/em; defaults to 180px-->\n}}\n\n'''''Ingenuity''''',<ref>''[https://mars.nasa.gov/news/8659/alabama-high-school-student-names-nasas-mars-helicopter/ Alabama High School Student Names NASA's Mars Helicopter].'' NASA, 29 April 2020.</ref> also known as '''Mars Helicopter''' (previously named the '''Mars Helicopter Scout'''<ref name=\"MHS\"/><ref name='distance'/>) is a planned robotic helicopter that will test the technology to scout interesting targets on [[Mars]], and help plan the best driving route for future Mars rovers.<ref name=\"drone1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.business2community.com/space-science/nasa-is-developing-a-helicopter-drone-for-2020-mars-mission-01138799 |title=NASA Is Developing A Helicopter Drone For 2020 Mars Mission |work=Business 2 Community |date=27 January 2015 |accessdate=28 January 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326071746/http://www.business2community.com/space-science/nasa-is-developing-a-helicopter-drone-for-2020-mars-mission-01138799 |archive-date=26 March 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Leone heli\">{{cite news |last=Leone |first=Dan |url=http://spacenews.com/elachi-touts-helicopter-scout-for-mars-sample-caching-rover/ |title=Elachi Touts Helicopter Scout for Mars Sample-Caching Rover |work=[[SpaceNews]] |date=19 November 2015 |accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe small drone helicopter will be deployed in 2021 from the planned [[Perseverance (rover)|''Perseverance'' rover]] as part of the [[Mars 2020]] mission. It is expected to fly up to five times during its 30-day test campaign, early in the rover's mission, as it is primarily a technology demonstration.<ref name=\"spacenews 20180504\">[http://spacenews.com/decision-expected-soon-on-adding-helicopter-to-mars-2020/ Decision expected soon on adding helicopter to Mars 2020]. Jeff Fout. ''Space News''. 4 May 2018.</ref>  Each flight will take no more than 3 minutes, at altitudes ranging from {{Val|3|to|10|u=m}} above the ground.<ref name=\"Balaram 2018\" /> It could potentially cover a distance of up to {{convert|300|m|abbr=on}} per flight.<ref name='Balaram 2018'/> It will use autonomous control and communicate with the ''Perseverance'' rover directly after each landing. \n\nIf it works as expected, NASA will be able to build on the design for future Mars lander missions.<ref name='Balaram 2018'>[https://rotorcraft.arc.nasa.gov/Publications/files/Balaram_AIAA2018_0023.pdf Mars Helicopter Technology Demonstrator]. (PDF) J. (Bob) Balaram, Timothy Canham, Courtney Duncan, Matt Golombek, H\u00e5vard Fj\u00e6r Grip, Wayne Johnson, Justin Maki, Amelia Quon, Ryan Stern, and David Zhu. American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics (AIAA), SciTech Forum Conference; 8\u201312 January 2018, Kissimmee, Florida. {{doi|10.2514/6.2018-0023}}.</ref> \n\n[[MiMi Aung]] is the project lead.<ref>[http://kiss.caltech.edu/lectures/Aung_Lecture_2015.html MiMi Aung - Autonomous Systems Deputy Division Manager]. NASA/JPL.</ref> Other contributors include [[AeroVironment |AeroVironment Inc]]., NASA [[Ames Research Center]], and NASA [[Langley Research Center]].<ref name=\"Witold 2018\">[https://rotorcraft.arc.nasa.gov/Publications/files/Koning_2018_TechMx.pdf Generation of Mars Helicopter Rotor Model for Comprehensive Analyses]. (PDF) Witold J. F. Koning, Wayne Johnson, Brian G. Allan. NASA Rotorcraft. 2018.</ref>\n\n==History==\nNASA's JPL and [[Caltech]] have been exploring the potential of sending an airborne scout robot to accompany the ''Perseverance'' rover, publishing the conceptual design of this helicopter in 2014.<ref name='Witold 2018'/><ref>J. Balaram and P. T. Tokumaru, \"Rotorcrafts for Mars Exploration,\" in 11th International Planetary Probe Workshop, 2014.</ref> \nBy mid 2016, $15 million was being requested to keep development of the helicopter on track.<ref>{{cite news |last=Berger |first=Eric |url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2016/05/four-wild-technologies-lawmakers-want-nasa-to-pursue/ |title=Four wild technologies lawmakers want NASA to pursue |work=ARS Technica |date=24 May 2016 |accessdate=24 May 2016}}</ref> By December 2017, engineering models of the vehicle had been tested in a simulated Martian atmosphere<ref name='Balaram 2018'/><ref name='Aung May2018'>[https://spaceflightnow.com/2018/05/14/helicopter-to-accompany-nasas-next-mars-rover-to-red-planet/ Helicopter to accompany NASA's next Mars rover to Red Planet]. Stephen Clarke, ''Spaceflight Now''. 14 May 2018.</ref> and models were undergoing testing in the Arctic, but its inclusion in the mission had not yet been approved nor funded.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.allaboutcircuits.com/news/nasa-projects-may-soon-use-drones-for-space-exploration-mars/ |title=Drones on Mars? NASA Projects May Soon Use Drones for Space Exploration |work=All About Circuits |first=Chantelle |last=Dubois |date=29 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States federal budget]] announced in March 2018, provided $23 million for the helicopter,<ref>[http://spacenews.com/nasa-mars-exploration-efforts-turn-to-operating-existing-missions-and-planning-sample-return/ NASA Mars exploration efforts turn to operating existing missions and planning sample return]. Jeff Foust, ''Space News''. 23 February 2018.</ref><ref>[https://spaceflightnow.com/2018/03/15/nasa-to-decide-soon-whether-flying-drone-will-launch-with-mars-2020-rover/ NASA to decide soon whether flying drone will launch with Mars 2020 rover]. Stephen Clarke, ''Spaceflight Now''. 15 March 2018.</ref> and it was announced on 11 May 2018 that the helicopter can be developed and tested in time to be included in the Mars 2020 mission.<ref name='HMS approved'>[https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/mars-helicopter-to-fly-on-nasa-s-next-red-planet-rover-mission Mars Helicopter to Fly on NASA's Next Red Planet Rover Mission]. Karen Northon, NASA News. 11 May 2018.</ref>\n\nThe helicopter underwent extensive flight-dynamics and environment testing,<ref name='Balaram 2018'/><ref name=\"NASA-20190328\">{{cite news |last1=Agle |first1=AG |last2=Johnson |first2=Alana |title=NASA's Mars Helicopter Completes Flight Tests |url=https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news.php?feature=7361 |date=28 March 2019 |work=[[NASA]] |accessdate=28 March 2019 }}</ref> and was then mounted on the underside of the ''Perseverance'' rover in August 2019.<ref name='Integrated'>[https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news.php?feature=7489 NASA's Mars Helicopter Attached to Mars 2020 Rover]. NASA News - JPL. 28 August 2019.</ref> Its mass is just under {{cvt|1.8|kg|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"NASA-20190328\" /> and it will make up to 5 flights.<ref name=SC2018>[https://www.space.com/40570-nasa-sending-helicopter-to-mars.html Yes, NASA Is Actually Sending a Helicopter to Mars: Here's What It Will Do.] Sarah Lewin, ''Space''. 12 May 2018.</ref><ref name='HMS approved'/>\n\n==Objectives==\nThe Mars Helicopter is a technology demonstrator by [[JPL]] that will assess whether this technology can fly safely, and provide better mapping and guidance that would give future mission controllers more information to help with travel routes planning and hazard avoidance, as well as identifying points of interest for the rover.<ref name=\"NASA-20180511b\">{{cite web |last1=Brown |first1=Dwayne |last2=Wendel |first2=JoAnna |last3=Agle |first3=DC |last4=Northon |first4=Karen |title=Mars Helicopter to Fly on NASA's Next Red Planet Rover Mission |url=https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/mars-helicopter-to-fly-on-nasa-s-next-red-planet-rover-mission |date=11 May 2018 |work=[[NASA]] |accessdate=11 May 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-20180511\">{{cite news |last=Chang |first=Kenneth |title=A Helicopter on Mars? NASA Wants to Try |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/11/science/mars-helicopter-nasa.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=12 May 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"VRG-20180511\">{{cite web |last=Gush |first=Loren |title=NASA is sending a helicopter to Mars to get a bird's-eye view of the planet - The Mars Helicopter is happening, y'all |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/5/11/17346414/nasa-mars-2020-helicopter-atmosphere |date=11 May 2018 |work=[[The Verge]] |accessdate=11 May 2018 }}</ref> The helicopter will provide overhead images with approximately ten times the resolution of orbital images, and would display features that may be occluded from the rover cameras.<ref>[https://solarsystem.nasa.gov/news/2015/01/22/helicopter-could-be-scout-for-mars-rovers Helicopter Could be 'Scout' for Mars Rovers]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. NASA News. 22 January 2015.</ref> It is expected that such scouting may enable future rovers to safely drive up to three times as far per [[Timekeeping on Mars|sol]].<ref>[http://epubs.surrey.ac.uk/841669/1/ScienceRobotics-SpaceRoboticsSurvey%20GaoChien_no%20figure_final.pdf Review on space robotics: Toward top-level science through space exploration] (PDF). Y Gao, S Chien - Science Robotics, 2017.</ref> \n\nThis test will form the foundation on which more capable helicopters can be developed for aerial exploration of Mars and other planetary targets with an atmosphere.<ref name=\"NASA-20180511b\"/><ref name='Balaram 2018'/><ref name='UB 2018'/>\n\n==Design==\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\" style=\"font-size:88%; margin-left:0.5em\"\n|-\n! Mars<br/>Helicopter Scout  !! Units/performance<ref name='distance'>[https://www.uasvision.com/2016/09/06/nasa-chooses-helicopter-for-mars-drone/ Mars Helicopter Scout]. video presentation at Caltech.</ref>\n|-\n| Mass|| Total: {{cvt|1.8|kg}}<ref name='distance'/> <br/>Batteries: 273 g <ref name='Balaram 2018'/>\n|-\n| Height || {{cvt|0.8|m}}<ref name='Aung May2018'/>\n|-\n| [[Coaxial rotor]] diameter || {{cvt|1.2|m}}<ref name='Aung May2018'/>\n|-\n| Revolutions/min || 1,900\u20132,800 rpm<ref name='HMS approved'/>\n|-\n| Blade tip speed || < 0.7 [[Mach number|Mach]]\n|-\n| Chassis dimension || {{cvt|14|cm}} cube\n|-\n| Power || {{cvt|220|W}}<br/>(battery, solar power charged)\n|-\n| Flight time || Up to 90 seconds, once per day\n|-\n| Operational time || ~5 flights in ~30 days\n|-\n| Maximum range || Flight: {{cvt|300|m}}<ref name='Balaram 2018'/><br/>Radio: {{cvt|1000|m}}<ref name='Balaram 2018'/>\n|-\n| Maximum altitude || {{cvt|10|m}}<ref name='Balaram 2018'/>\n|-\n| Maximum speed<ref name='Witold 2018'/> || Horizontal: {{cvt|10|m/s}}  <br/>Vertical: {{cvt|3|m/s}} \n|-\n| 2 cameras || High resolution imagery in color.<br/>Navigation.<ref name='Aung May2018'/> \n|}\n[[File:MarsRoverHelicopter-20150122.png|thumb|left|200px|Mars Helicopter<br>(artist concept)]]\nThe helicopter uses counter-rotating [[coaxial rotors]] about {{cvt|1.1|m}} in diameter. Its payload will be a high resolution downward-looking camera for navigation, landing, and science surveying of the terrain, and a communication system to relay data to the 2020 Mars rover.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www-robotics.jpl.nasa.gov/publications/Richard_Volpe/isairas%202014%20paper,%20volpe,%20v8.pdf |format=PDF |title=2014 Robotics Activities at JPL |last=Volpe |first=Richard |work=Jet Propulsion Laboratory |accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref> Although it is an aircraft, it is being constructed as a spacecraft in order to endure the g-force and vibration during launch. It also includes radiation-resistant systems capable of operating in the frigid environment of Mars.\n\nThe inconsistent Mars magnetic field precludes the use of a [[compass]] for navigation, so it will use a [[solar tracker]] camera integrated to JPL's visual [[inertial navigation system]]. Some additional inputs include [[gyroscope|gyros]], [[visual odometry]], [[Inclinometer|tilt sensors]], [[altimeter]], and hazard detectors.<ref>[https://thesis.library.caltech.edu/10338/1/Parth_Shah_2017Thesis.pdf Heading Estimation via Sun Sensing for Autonomous Navigation]. Parth Shah. 2017.</ref> It will use [[solar panels on spacecraft|solar panels]] to recharge its batteries, which are six Sony [[Li-ion]] cells with a nameplate capacity of 2 [[Ampere hour|Ah]].<ref name='Balaram 2018'/>\n\nThe prototype uses the [[Qualcomm Snapdragon|Snapdragon processor]] from [[Intrinsyc]] with a [[Linux]] operating system,<ref name='Balaram 2018'/> which also implements visual navigation via a velocity estimate derived from features tracked with a camera.<ref name='Balaram 2018'/> The processor is connected to two flight-control Microcontroller Units (MCU) to perform the needed flight-control functions.<ref name='Balaram 2018'/> Communications with the rover are through a radio link called [[Zig-Bee]], a standard 900&nbsp;MHz chipset that are mounted in both the rover and helicopter.<ref name='Balaram 2018'/> The communication system is designed to relay data at 250 kbit/s over distances of up to {{cvt|1000|m}}.<ref name='Balaram 2018'/>\n\nThe helicopter will travel to Mars attached to the underside of the ''Perseverance'' rover, and will be deployed to the surface between 60 and 90 [[Timekeeping on Mars|Martian days]] after the landing. Then, the rover will drive approximately {{cvt|100|m}} away for the test flights to begin.<ref>[http://www.ibtimes.com/nasas-mars-helicopter-small-autonomous-rotorcraft-fly-red-planet-2680575 \"NASA's Mars Helicopter: Small, Autonomous Rotorcraft To Fly On Red Planet\"]. Shubham Sharma, ''International Business Times''. 14 May 2018.</ref><ref name='Universe2018'>[https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/universe/archive/universe1807.pdf Mars Helicopter a new challenge for flight]. ''Universe - JPL - July 2018\". Accessed: 20 July 2018.</ref>\n\n==Future==\nThis technology demonstration will form the foundation on which more capable helicopters can be developed for more ambitious missions to planets and moons with an atmosphere.<ref name='Balaram 2018'/><ref name='UB 2018'>[https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/universe/archive/universe1807.pdf Mars Helicopter a new challenge for flight]. NASA JPL: Universe Bulletin, July 2018. Accessed: 9 August 2018.</ref> The next generation of rotorcraft may be in the range between 5 and 15&nbsp;kg with science payloads between 0.5 and 1.5&nbsp;kg. These potential aircraft could have direct communication to an orbiter and may or may not continue to work with a landed asset.<ref name='Universe2018'/> Future helicopters could be used to explore special regions with exposed [[Water on Mars|water ice or brines]] where Earth microbial life could potentially survive.\n\nMars helicopters may also be considered for fast retrieval of small sample caches back to a Mars ascent vehicle for return to Earth.<ref name='Balaram 2018'/>\n\n==Gallery==\n{{Multiple image |align=center |caption_align=center |perrow=3 |total_width= |title=Mars Helicopter ''Ingenuity'' |image1=PIA22460-Mars2020Mission-Helicopter-20180525.jpg |caption1=Solar powered helicopter drone to be tested as navigation aid |width1=290 |image2=PIA23771-Mars2020-Helicopter-20200312.jpg |caption2=Mars Helicopter ''Ingenuity''|width2=290|image3= NASA-MarsHelicopterIngenuity-20200429.webm |caption3=''Ingenuity'' helicopter demostration<br />[[:File:NASA-MarsHelicopterIngenuity-20200429.webm|(1:07; animation; 29 April 2020)]] |width3=290 |footer= }}\n{{multipleimage |header=[[Mars 2020|''Perseverance'' rover]] assembly (2019) |align=center |direction=horizontal |width= |image1=PIA23372-16-BuildingMars2020Rover-AttachingHelicopter-20190828.jpg |caption1=<div align=\"center\">Helicopter attachment to the underside of the rover</div> |width1=342 |image2=PIA23317-Mars2020Helicopter-Team-20190730.jpg |caption2=<div align=\"center\">Helicopter and team members</div> |width2=257 |image3=PIA23153-BuildingMars2020Rover-AttachingHelicopter-20190828.jpg |caption3=<div align=\"center\">Helicopter adjustments</div> |width3=290 |footer= }}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Mars aircraft]]\n* {{annotated link|Aerial Regional-scale Environmental Survey|ARES|}}\n* {{annotated link|Sky-Sailor}}\n* [[Dragonfly (spacecraft)|Dragonfly]] \u2013 Robotic [[rotorcraft]] mission to [[Titan (moon)|Titan]], launching in 2026\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons cat}}\n* [https://mars.nasa.gov/technology/helicopter/ NASA Mars Helicopter webpage]\n*[https://rotorcraft.arc.nasa.gov/Publications/files/Balaram_AIAA2018_0023.pdf Mars Helicopter Technology Demonstrator]. (PDF) \u2014 The key design features of the prototype drone.\n\n{{Mars 2020}}\n{{Mars spacecraft}}\n\n[[Category:Coaxial rotor helicopters]]\n[[Category:Electric helicopters]]\n[[Category:Extraterrestrial aircraft]]\n[[Category:Mars 2020|*]]\n[[Category:Missions to Mars]]\n[[Category:NASA aircraft]]\n[[Category:Proposed aircraft]]\n[[Category:2020 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:Unmanned helicopters]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout, and guidelines. -->\n{{short description|A planned robotic Mars aircraft}}\n{{about|the planned NASA robotic helicopter being deployed on Mars in 2021|Mars helicopters in general|Mars aircraft}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name                  = Ingenuity\n| names_list            = Mars Helicopter Scout<ref name=\"MHS\">\"[https://pub-lib.jpl.nasa.gov/docushare/dsweb/Get/Document-3749/03_Rotorcrafts%20For%20Mars%20Exploration_Balaram.pdf Rotorcrafts for Mars Exploration: Mars Helicopter Scout]\" \u2013 [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]], 19 June 2014</ref><ref name='distance'/>\n\n<!--image of the spacecraft/mission-->\n| image                 = File:PIA22460-Mars2020Mission-Helicopter-20180525 (cropped).jpg\n| image_caption         = Artist conc